Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels — Over most of the past decade, central banks have made only limited progress in countering strong global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the Federal Reserve has kept interest rates at zero and also conducted multiple unprecedented balance sheet expansions through large-scale bond purchases.
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank have also followed the Federal Reserve's lead, each implementing their own version of so-called "quantitative easing" (QE).
But inflation has not seen a reasonable increase anywhere.
Although these countries have been fighting deflationary pressures, their monetary policies — and economic performance — are diverging.
The United States and the United Kingdom now have strong enough growth to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, while the eurozone and Japan are increasing QE, pushing policy-driven long-term interest rates further into negative territory.
Why is there this divergence?
The short answer is debt.
For decades, the United States and the United Kingdom have had current account deficits, making them debtors, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditors.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor countries but are detrimental to creditor countries, which is why the negative interest rate introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated the recovery of the United States and the United Kingdom, but had little effect on the eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor countries around the world — countries with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland — have experienced negative interest rates, not only for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debt, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is far from good.
Although low interest rates have had limited effectiveness, central banks in these economies still persist with this policy.
If you argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot bring benefits to the economy, they will change the subject and refute the idea that raising interest rates can stimulate the economy — which appears flawless at first glance.
But in reality, this argument is full of loopholes.
Basic economics courses have mentioned this peculiar phenomenon called "the backward-sloping savings supply curve": in certain environments, lowering interest rates leads to an increase in savings.
This is because a decrease in interest rates reduces the income of savers, who will then cut back on spending, especially if they have savings goals for retirement.
All of this does not否定 the general rule — which forms the foundation of modern monetary decision-making — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other spending.
The impact varies depending on the debt situation of the economy.
In a closed economy, every creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what creditors lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with a large net foreign asset position, creditors are naturally more numerous than debtors.
For a country with a large amount of foreign debt, the situation is exactly the opposite.
Therefore, the effects of interest rate lower bound monetary policy differ between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important, as foreign asset positions were often small (as a percentage of GDP).
However, now, foreign asset positions in major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, in part due to the leverage that caused the 2007–2008 global financial crisis.
In fact, leverage is still continuing to increase at the country level.
Although current account imbalances have eased somewhat since the financial crisis began, they have not reversed.
This means surplus countries continue to strengthen their creditor positions, while diverging from deficit economies.
Some commodity-exporting countries, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, have had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, making them a major exception to the divergence in foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have plummeted, reversing the wealth trends of these countries.
Their export revenues have sharply declined — many countries have lost half — forcing them to run deficits, relying on their vast sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the global commodities boom.
Now, a significant reduction in spending has become inevitable.
Industrialized economies face entirely different challenges.
Their problem — to some extent, a problem of luxury — is ensuring that consumers spend the windfall from falling import prices.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates seem not to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence also exists within the eurozone.
Although as a whole, the eurozone is a creditor economy, there are also debtor countries within it.
Debtor economies, such as Spain and Portugal, now have current account surpluses and are gradually reducing their debt.
But the current account surpluses of traditional debtor countries are too high, leading to continued increases in the debtor/creditor asymmetry.
The most notable point is that since the outbreak of the financial crisis, Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP, meaning that the surplus accumulated during this period exceeds the previous historical total.
Following the current trend, Germany's creditor position may rise from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend of central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less eager to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem to lack patience, struggling with low inflation, despite the output gap slowly being closed, and the United States and Japan have achieved full employment.
Central bank governors in debtor countries must stop manipulating the economy with more monetary easing that may be detrimental to production.
Instead, they should allow the recovery to develop on its own, even if it is very slow, and wait for the base effect of falling oil prices to disappear.
ECB President Draghi recently acknowledged that, in today's global environment, the current monetary policy approach may not be effective.
But promising more of the same is not the solution.
